, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L\left(u\right)=\int_{0}^{1}\sqrt{1+\left(u'\right)^{2}}\d x.\label{eq:p1-a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

In fact, consider the infinitesimal patch of the chain from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,u\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+\d x,u+\d u\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be smooth, so this patch can be approximated by a straight
 segment which has length
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\d L=\sqrt{\d x^{2}+\d u^{2}}=\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{\d u}{\d x}\right)^{2}}\d x=\sqrt{1+\left(u'\right)^{2}}\d x.\label{eq:p1-a-diff-form}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, Eqn.
 
