Show that the potential energy of the chain, 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(u\right)$
\end_inset

, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(u\right)=\int_{0}^{1}\rho gu\sqrt{1+\left(u'\right)^{2}}\d x.\label{eq:p1-b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For convenience, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho g=1$
\end_inset

 for al subsequent problems.
\end_layout

\end_inset

In fact, consider the patch of the chain from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,u\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+\d x,u+\d u\right)$
\end_inset

 once more.
 We approximate this patch by a straight segment which has length 
\begin_inset Formula $\d L=\sqrt{1+\left(u'\right)^{2}}\d x$
\end_inset

 and the center is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+\frac{1}{2}\d x,u+\frac{1}{2}\d u\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the potential energy of the patch, defined as the product of mass,
 gravity constant, and altitude, reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\d E & =\left(\rho\d L\right)g\left(u+\frac{1}{2}\d u\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\rho ug\d L+\cO\left(\d x^{2}\right).\label{eq:p1-b-diff-form}
\end{align}

\end_inset

